segments.text: David Ogden is a stupid fool who will get beat on the tennis court.
This is a test, but true.
This is an interview with General Andrews.
Today is the 3rd of August, 1981.
This is Terry Anderson.
Let's start, General, with where and when you were born, and then let's talk about your parents.
I was born on a farm.
about 12 miles northeast of Caldwell, Texas, on August the 22nd, 1916.
My father was a rancher, small ranch, small cattle.
But his primary position was a wildcat oil driller.
He drilled several wells, and one specifically, which was a dry well, was on the
property in Snook, Texas, which is now a very productive well here recently.
Unfortunately, he died at the age of 34 and caused what we now call hepatitis.
Then they called it yellow jaundice.
But he'd been very prosperous in terms of prosperity at that time in that he had
at that early age had bought and paid for the farm, had several hundred head of cattle, and was one of the first ones to have a Ford, a Model T, with bumpers as a kid.
I remember that because we went to Caldwell and a crowd farmed around it, looking at these bumpers, you know, really fancy.
But he died at that early age.
I was only five years old.
Do you remember how large the farm was?
Well, I still have it.
Oh, you do?
It's 151 acres that we owned, but at that time, the range was open.
You could go, so cattle ran outside.
In addition, usually the farm produced corn and beet stuff, and cotton, too.
Most of it was beet stuff.
And from our farm, you could go eight miles to the railroad.
That was all open land, no fencing.
And you could go towards the community of Hicks six miles in that direction with no fences.
And so the cattle would run free except those with cans or to keep those up.
And with bells on them.
And we had different tone bells.
And you could go out and look for them.
And you could hear and recognize which small herd because they weren't all together.
But then after he passed away,
When was that?
In the 1920s?
Well, let me see.
I was five years old, so five was 1921.
My mother moved to Caldwell, and it was kind of downhill, and the Depression was going on.
I had a sister.
She's deceased now.
For us to go to school, I wasn't old enough to go to school, but she went to school.
She worked as a seamstress, because when he died, all income stopped.
Of course, we still had the farm, but the kids had to have an education.
So we moved to Caldwell, and she was a seamstress.
And she remained single to put us through school, which she did.
I graduated from Caldwell High School in 1934.
But during those years, even though we would be considered poor, we didn't know we were poor.
We had enough to eat and clothes to wear.
We didn't have a car.
That car I just described, that Model T, was sitting back on the farm in a shed.
And it deteriorated through the years, which is really pitiful.
We finally sold it out for a small amount.
But we had a car.
My mother didn't drive and couldn't support a car anyway.
My grandparents lived on the farm and continued on with the, well, very few cattle.
I mean, everything went down thanks to what my father had done.
What type of education did your father have?
He didn't graduate from high school.
I think he went through about the ninth grade and went immediately into business in the oil business.
And how he got started in the oil business at that early age,
His brother-in-law in Beaumont, Texas was out in Spinnletop.
They had a lease out there.
The Spinnletop boom happened a few years before, early 1900s.
But it was still a boom.
I'll never forget going out to Spinnletop the first time.
You just see acres and acres of oil wells, derricks.
Of course, they did it differently.
because you put up a permanent derrick because every few months you had what they call pull the well.
You had to pull out all those pipes and flush out because the mud type of formation would get there and slow down the flow.
So they used those derricks for that purpose.
And so every derrick had a lot of long pipes in reserve.
He loved his horse.
I remember that the horse was named Jim.
And he would ship his horse to Beaumont.
So each time he'd go, in those days it was simple because all you had to do was call up the Santa Fe Railroad and order a stock cart.
And it would stop and just lead the horse right aboard.
And you could either ride with the animal
in the caboose or, of course, take a passenger train, which you usually take a passenger train because you'd be there ready to see the horse.
Do you ever remember if your father died when you were five, do you ever remember him?
Oh, yeah.
What were your impressions?
What type of man he was?
Tremendous.
Of course, being five years old, obviously, you feel attached to your father because he would play with me.
He was a member of the
Masons and Woodman of the World, I guess, or the other.
And his watchbot was here, and I remember I used to, he'd throw me up, and I'd crawl around and play with that watchbot.
And he was driving the car, as I described, when we went to Caldwell on that particular occasion.
I remember him saddling up the horse, which was a beautiful horse, a gun horse named Jim.
And he's very devoted to his children and to his wife.
Now, he met my mother, and this is interesting too.
In those days, Bell Telephone didn't, it wasn't even existence in the countryside.
It existed somewhere, I'm sure.
But the telephone service was privately owned.
He, in addition to the cattle, had been an oil and wild cattle.
He owned a division, meaning that he owned the,
telephones and also the line.
And it goes into a switchboard.
My mother, when she was a young girl, was a switchboard operator at Goss, Texas.
Now, you know, it's practically nothing but a few stores.
But that used to be, you know, cotton gin there and banks and just all the train stops there.
It was sort of a business center.
She was a switchboard operator.
And my father's part of the line went in to the switchboard at Goss.
So he met my mother then.
First time he ever heard of her.
He talked to her on the telephone, you know.
So he asked her for a date and that sort of thing.
So that's how their romance commenced.
How much education did your mother have?
Just about ninth grade also.
And that's because they attended country schools.
Sure, and that's pretty cool.
And then they didn't have buses, and it's too far to ride a horse.
They'll bug you if you're out in the boondocks.
So they'd go to the local school.
In fact, my mother attended a school in the community of Hicks when she was growing up as a girl.
And my father attended a school.
They don't have it anymore.
In fact, the community's not even there.
I can't even remember the name of it.
Anyway, it was a vicinity where he bought the farm.
What type of character or person was your mom?
Real strong.
Strong-willed?
Oh, yeah.
She's a, well, to say she raised us.
Sure.
She remarried, actually, while I was at A&M.
She stayed single all when she was young and beautiful, really.
And she had several opportunities to marry, but she didn't want her children to be stepchildren.
So my sister was teaching school, and I actually married when my mother remarried.
And then I was, I guess I was a junior at the end.
She married a real fine guy.
He's deceased too, both my mother and her father.
His name was Renfro.
But she is a very strong-willed woman.
Woman determined?
That's right.
What else?
Very religious.
And what religion?
Baptist.
Strong Baptist.
I'm a Methodist, and so is my wife.
I chained over.
Oh, yes, she was a really devoted Methodist.
I'm Baptist.
She'd never miss a Sunday going to church.
And she took the children?
Oh, yes.
How many brothers and sisters did you have?
Just a sister.
And what happened to her?
or is she still living?
No, she graduated from high school in Caldwell and she went to college for two years with Beaumont and Lamar.
I think Lamar had a different name.
So she went there two years and she lived with my father's sister in Brooklyn, LaPilps.
They had a great big
two-story house on a great, I guess, about an acre.
So she stayed there.
But she fell in love with Frank Bowers, who's also from Caldwell.
Frank Bowers had to graduate from high school.
He went to University of Texas.
He became a pharmacist.
And so they lived in Houston.
He was a pharmacist out in that hospital complex.
Nothing.
It's a big pharmacy that supported two or three of the hospital.
He's still alive, but my sister died at age 58 of cancer.
As far as leadership is concerned, you said that your father was in a lot of organizations.
Was he the leader of any of those organizations?
Not to my knowledge, no.
Was your mother in any social organizations back in Colville?
Well, she belonged to the... Woman's clubs or anything?
Well, she also, the Woodman's of the World also, I think they have a ladies auxiliary.
She belonged to that.
But she worked.
She worked long hours.
And she didn't get much money for it either.
But you know, in those days, a dollar a day was just about the going wage.
And anybody that made more than that was a lot of people.
Just like when we would get to A&M, I worked for $0.25 an hour.
Been delighted to get it.
Now, when you came home from school, who took care of you and your sister?
Well, my mother did because she was working.
She was a seamstress then at home?
Yeah.
OK.
It was a big two-story house in Caldwell.
It's no longer there, right on the courthouse square.
And she worked with a lady named Mrs. Purdue.
The two of them worked together.
And they had their sewing room in the front part of the house.
And Mrs. Perdue had an apartment, two or three rooms.
And we had two rooms.
So when we'd come home, of course, we'd check in there.
But like all kids, I was ended because I lived right in town.
There was a lot of kids that lived across from the jail, for example.
And that was always interesting with the prison and stuff.
And we used to run errands for them.
You must go get some tobacco or some stuff.
You got to send the money down in a can on a string.
But speaking of leadership or influence, and I think.
And what way did your parents influence you toward leadership, do you think?
Your mother.
I don't know.
They just wanted me to excel.
To do right and to attend school and be all of the standards that you would expect as parents.
But see, I had no father, had no male influence, but the one who really had influence on me growing up in school was a football coach.
Okay.
Let's talk about him.
What was his name?
Darby.
E.E.
Darby.
His nickname was Ox.
And he's still alive, and he's over in Colorado now, retired.
Great big guy.
He was a star for four years at San Marcos.
Then that was Southwest Teachers College, I think they called it there.
And he was a captain for two years, junior and senior year.
So he had all those sweaters, those days they gave sweaters.
He had them all the way from one strike to the
Those were the end of his senior year.
He had two stars for being a captain, you know, his junior year, and then another strike.
And he was a real solid, fine individual.
A disciplinarian, by the way.
Mimi.
I'm sorry to interrupt.
I'm a fellow.
I'd like you to meet my wife, Mimi.
Oh, how are you?
Well, go on with your talk.
OK.
I apologize.
I can't offer you much.
It's all right.
I didn't have food.
Okay.
Let's continue then about your coach.
He was a, as I was saying, he was a disciplinarian.
Max Darby.
And, of course, like I do now, but also there, not only did he coach baseball, football, basketball, track, but carried a pretty heavy academic load.
Taught civics and history.
And he did all of those well.
He didn't smoke.
He didn't drink until immediately.
And he had no patience for any high school kid that would smoke.
And of course, it appealed on us, because we were just doing our best to please him, to keep him conditioned.
I wasn't very large.
In fact, my senior year, I weighed 150 pounds.
But I really put out.
And he was my model, male model.
Of course, I never aspired to be a college football player.
I just thought if I could live my life like him, I figured I'd be a great asset.
The other one that had a tremendous influence on me was the president of the Caldwell National Bank named C.C.
Nell.
How do you spell that last name?
N-E-L-L-M-S. And of course he's long deceased.
But he was a kind,
He was the grandfather of my good friend, Nettie Kaye, who he too is deceased now.
So that's how I got to know him.
And he accepted me and his wife and their home just as if I was one of the family.
What type of person was he?
Well, he was a very religious individual.
fault that I know that he ever had.
He chewed the backer, but he did it in a way that you had to really know him to know because a great golfer.
We didn't have a golf course in Caldwell then.
They have a nine hole course there now.
So he played in Bryan.
He doesn't go to church as much as I want to because Sunday was his golf playing day.
So I was going over to Bryan.
But he was a very good man.
And he helped me out on several occasions.
For example,
When I was going to A&M my junior year, I had no money to buy boots for the senior year and so forth.
So the association of ex-students, I guess they still do that.
You could borrow money from them.
So I borrowed money, and you need somebody to co-sign a note.
And I went into Mr. Naum, and he said, well, this is kind of unusual for a banker to be co-signing somebody else's note.
that I'm happy to help you.
So after graduation and I got the money and paid him back, I brought that council note back to him and he liked it and wanted to question his mind about it.
But those were probably the two male models since I had no father that I really respected and admired.
And what did you learn from these two?
How did they influence you?
Well, probably a male lifestyle.
Darby being much younger and being disciplined and having high standards, both physically, obviously, but also moral standards.
Nem's the same thing.
Darby was single at the time.
Later on, he married.
But Nem's had this big home, nice furniture, and happiness, and he just said, well,
if you're going to strive for a goal in the community, I would like to be patterned after Ox Darby and attain the level of success as Nelms did, or was at that time.
Were they leaders in their own right?
Well, Nelms was.
He was a leader of the Chamber of Commerce.
Darby was a leader because he won district
nearly every year.
In fact, the last time I talked to him, I asked him, say, in your lifetime, one loss, what was it?
You know, you're always talking about Bear Bryant and all that.
That's the way that you majored.
He said, I really don't know.
I said, well, we didn't win district the year I played, but you won it the year before.
In fact, they won by district.
He said, well, we had some rough years also.
But he said, every time I was down and had a bad year, they'd get ready to fire me.
Just before they fired me, we had a successful year.
So he was a football coach there for, I guess, 25 years.
And I wish I knew he had won a loss record, because I know it is really a fair favor.
Because he just didn't lose in any game.
But we won more games the year that I played
I was out for four years.
I came out when I was a freshman.
I was a scrub, you know.
And what position did you play?
In, right in.
But my senior year, I made the team and played right in and didn't miss a quarter the entire season.
In those days...
Were you a tight end?
Well, we didn't.
Different formations.
And you played offense and defense.
And you really had to be hurt to be taken out of the game because
After you once was taken out in a quarter, you couldn't come back that quarter.
And you had four quarters.
And you played offensive defense.
You didn't have near the number two.
And a formation that then we had a short punt formation.
They called it short punt because you weren't going to punt, but you lined up very similar.
And of course, you had double wing back.
Center always centered, you know, back.
In other words, you sort of play, call it a shotgun now, but that's what you played every time then because just getting the quarterback underneath the center, that's a late development.
Were you in other sports?
Well, I played basketball, but I never was on it.
I went out for everything.
What about other activities in school?
Scouting, I was a big boy scout.
Very active in the church.
Baptist, you know that?
B-Y-P-U, Baptist Young Peoples.
I even, and I was very religious in the sense that I participated in all the activities.
We had a prayer meeting on Wednesday night.
All of the young people did.
They didn't have TV.
Radio was just coming along.
And it was static.
It was terrible.
So the church and school was our whole entire element in life.
And not many cars.
All families didn't have cars.
Those that did, well, the reason I say we didn't have a car, but I didn't know it was poor,
My friends had a car.
And they treated me as if I had a car.
It wasn't the case that you get your car today and I get mine.
So I'd say the church and the school, and we were very much closer to teachers then than children are now.
We called us a school activity.
Plays, for example, that was a big deal, you know, playing.
Trying out for the plays and putting on the plays.
But sports I loved, even though I was small.
I went out and did my best to ever win, including track.
Were you a leader in any of these groups?
No, I wouldn't say I was a leader.
You participated, but were you like the president of the student finance or the captain of the football team?
No, I was never captain of the football team.
So your leadership ability came later.
Well, I wouldn't be so.
arrogant to say that leadership, I've been lucky all my life.
Things turned out for me.
You might even say maybe leadership was thrust upon me.
Well, you assumed the role of leadership then later in your life.
I would say that without being a president of any society or activity, I was considered a leader in our group.
in the church.
Sort of an informal leader.
In what way?
Well, the ones who suggest doing certain things.
We had a quartet.
I can't sing, but at least I was in a quartet.
And I'd be the one who would suggest maybe when we would rehearse, or where we would rehearse, and that sort of thing.
Along, of course, with the support of the one who's functioning at the time.
What were your favorite subjects when you were in high school?
I guess history was one of my favorites.
You mean what other besides history?
No, just... Would you have considered yourself well-liked or popular in high school?
Yeah.
I played in the band all the time.
I went out for all activities.
Seems like you did everything.
How were your grades?
About average.
I had one or two teachers, but I was sort of a favorite.
I got better grades than them.
Really a good-looking woman.
Of course, she was young.
She looked old, didn't she?
And named Miss Welch.
But all through school, as you know, as your name starts today, you always get seated in the front.
And now nearly every class, we're sitting up first seat or right near the teacher.
But I think history is the thing because it intrigued me, especially to read and study about outstanding people.
There have been forms of mankind and culture
Now, when you graduated in 1934, did you have a firm set of aims?
I mean, did you know exactly what you wanted?
Did you have any idea of what you wanted to become in future life?
Yep.
What was that?
Well, I wanted to be a professional lawyer, but I wanted to be a professional soldier.
You did?
Yeah.
Did you have any taste of the military before you graduated from high school?
You see that I was a joiner.
I joined the National Guard when I was in high school.
I was very naive because I didn't realize I was falsified when I signed it.
And nobody said, hey, you're supposed to be 18 years old.
You're not 18 yet.
And the reason why there was no problem with that is that
The National Guard in those days, very small.
We had, I think, 110 in the company in Caldwell.
They had a company there, infantry.
And I've already mentioned, first I was a Boy Scout.
I loved the uniforms.
I liked to camp out and do those things.
And I was in the band, playing in the band.
And there was an officer in National Guard Austin, Waco, named Napoleon Rainbow.
He says, in addition to the 143rd band, says, this summer at Palacios, Texas, we want to have a drum and bugle corps.
So he sent out the word.
Well, our company commander, named Ockridge at the time, asked if we were interested in joining the National Guard and going to Summer County.
I said, oh, yeah.
Well, I get very much since I played the drum, snare drum.
That was my thing.
So I joined the National Guard and went there and liked it very much.
And so I continued on participating in the drills.
Of course, once again, those days you got a dollar for drills once a week.
Sure.
That was a lot of money for a kid in high school.
And so I continued on.
And then when I went to A&M,
I didn't know at the time, but you just didn't join the National Guard.
And then when you stopped going to drill, they dropped your name ball.
You were put into the, I think it's called now, inactive reserve.
But you're still not only eligible, but you still really have a commitment to continue on to fulfill your enlistment.
Well, later on, it turned out
Fine, because when World War II came along, lo and behold, I found that I could claim longevity pay because they forgave anybody and you could go back.
Anybody who signed up, regardless if you were 16 or 17 or whatever it was, you were still a member since you had that commitment.
And they overlooked, I guess is a better word, it was a law that said all service before age 18
We'll count for long days.
Now, I wanted a career in the military.
I wanted to go to A&M.
Why?
The seniors, that's the reason why I have boots and spurs.
It really has an impression on you.
I like scouts.
I like the military.
And there weren't many people graduating, going to A&M.
This was all during the Depression and before then, I think.
So they would come from A&M to Caldwell for whatever reason, the seniors, with their boots on.
I'll buy a guy some day, I don't know, a lot of those boots.
And I'm not proud of them, I don't have any money.
So once again, I was lucky.
Doc Mize had been
became the band leader at Allen Military Academy.
I don't know what ever happened to Doc Meyers, but he was a well-known individual.
At Baylor, he had a band, and his claim to fame was he could play two clarinets at the same time.
Two reeds, and then his clarinet ended for long.
So he had just arrived at Allen Academy,
And Nat Allen, this is the old man, I don't know, did you know Nat Allen, Jr.?
Of course, he's about my age, he's not so young.
This is his father, who owned Allen Academy, being then a private, he owned it the other time.
So he was expanding his band.
So he came over and talked to me and said, say, why don't you come to Allen Academy?
I said, I'd be delighted, but I don't have any money.
He said, well, I can get you a scholarship.
You work in the mess as a waiter.
But you'll have to raise some money for tuition.
It wasn't very much, but the main cost was a room and board.
My sister was teaching school, and she could loan me the money for the tuition.
So I got the Allen Academy.
And now I was a stepping stone, hopefully, to A&M.
But also, there was a possibility that I could get an appointment at the military academy because it was an ROTC honor-rated school, and they took one graduate each year to the military academy.
So I thought maybe this would be my break.
So I went to school there, but unfortunately for me, there's an officer from West Texas named Windorf.
from the town.
You know, there's a lot of Czechs and he's a Czech.
West Texas is a Czech community.
And he was really good in math.
So he got the appointment for the military academy.
Now my problem, how am I going to A&M?
Still no money.
So... How long did you stay at Allen?
One year.
Actually, Allen at that time was one year and a half.
And you can transfer
I don't know what it's called.
It's a junior college now, ain't it?
No.
It's back to a high school.
And A&M would accept.
So many students went there, and then went to A&M, and their sophomore year transferred.
So I can't recall his name now, but he was married to Nat Allen's
sister, of course the Allen family owned the school.
And he talked to me and he was the assistant to the head of the dairy husbandry department, C.N.
Sheperson.
I think he's deceased now too, I think I read it several years ago.
But he was the head of the, well he became head of the, what's the department now?
Agricultural department, do they have that now?
That's a dean, isn't it?
Well, he was a dean then, Dean Shepparton.
So he told me if I wanted to go to A&M, he thinks he could get me in with a job.
But I'd have to major in dairy husbandry.
I said, I don't care what the major is.
I just want to go to A&M.
So he arranged for me to go in the summer, the fall .
So I transferred my credits.
So I was down on the old dairy farm.
Then on the dairy farm, it's all gone now.
Behind the creamery, there was a row, eight single houses.
Each of those, one was occupied by an employee with his family.
The rest of them were rooms that students could live in while they were going to school.
So I got a job, 25 cents an hour, shoveling manure.
And you know, the dairy cattle go all around.
And then when they took them into the stall, the milking they had.
You'd shovel it out?
Yeah, to clean out all that stuff.
You'd put it into a wagon.
And some of the other tasks was hay.
I remember that was the toughest job, unloading hay off of a truck.
And you had to put it way up in the top.
of the barn, and it was hot inside.
So that was the type of work I was doing during the summer, and going to summer school.
Then I discovered, to my chagrin and shock, that I wasn't on the list to live in those houses during the fall, because they had commitment to the others.
They were coming back.
Where did you live?
Well, this employee, and I can't remember his last name.
His first name was Joe.
He heard about my plight, and he said, say, I'll tell you what.
I'll fix up my back porch.
It was partially enclosed anyway with glass, but not all of it.
But he said, I can get a map down on the screen here, and that still is going to be pretty cold, but it doesn't make any difference because I want to sleep there.
And so I started out that way.
So my first year at A&M, I lived on the back porch of one of those houses.
The next year, of course, I got a roof with a roof maker.
In what dorm?
Pardon?
In what dorm?
No, not on campus.
Oh, still on campus.
Still down in the town.
In fact, I lived there the entire time.
So it was convenient to work there.
My working hours, we used to get up at 4 o'clock in the morning and work in the creamery and work until first class.
Of course, leaving in time to walk on campus.
Well, that's really on campus, quick walk through the classroom.
But the next year, I was able to work in the creamery.
Now, that was a real good job, you see, because you wore white starch coveralls
what you do for a pasteurized milk.
First, starting off like I was, the bottom of a washed bottle.
Then we haul the milk to the dining hall, and we bring back the empty bottles.
Of course, we have to wash them and pasteurize the milk, fill them up, and get them back in routine like that.
So in the creamery, that was the least desirable job.
And I spent most of my time doing that the first year in the creamery.
But my junior and senior year, I was pasteurized milk, made cottage cheese, make ice cream, you know, that sort of thing.
All of them were real nice jobs.
What corps are you in, where you're with?
Well, I was with the infantry.
C Company.
They had a... See, I was known as a day dodger.
Everybody then lived in the
in the dormitory, or halls in the dormitory halls.
Everybody wore a uniform.
Even if you only had one leg, you wore a uniform.
You were non-military, but you wore a uniform and you were subject.
It was patterned out to the military cap.
Exactly right.
There were some of us who lived off campus or out of the halls.
Well, some lived in brines, particularly non-military.
But it was really a fine school.
I think it's great now, but it's a different school now.
This was a... Let's talk about the Depression for a minute.
How did the Depression affect your upbringing?
Well, I think it had a very positive influence.
In what way?
learn to appreciate small things, learning to get by and be happy with very little.
In some way, I guess a print to my mother, I said that I never compared my life and say I got a dirty deal.
We're living on the poverty line.
All the things they emphasize now, you know, ghettos and all that.
